segments.text: Okay, now, your name is Augustine?
Augustine C. Garcia.
Augustine C. Garcia.
Yeah, always I say C, but my whole name is always C. Okay.
Okay.
Okay, we're here on Highway 79 East.
Right, east of Rockdale.
What, about one mile east of Rockdale?
A mile and a half, they call it.
That's what my car raced, the speedometer.
Okay.
Yeah, one and a half miles.
Right, and it's about ten minutes to three in the afternoon.
I guess it is.
Okay, all right.
Now, may I call you Augustine?
Sure, yeah, sure.
All right.
Did you grow up in the United States, or were you born somewhere else?
I was born in Travis County.
Travis County.
In Austin, Texas.
No kidding.
Right.
And how did you get to Rockville?
Well, you know, before up in them days, there was traveling, you know, working.
He was working on farms.
And we moved out here to San Diego, they tell me, when I was about seven years old.
from Bastrop, San Diego, San Diego, they were just starting the lignite works around here.
And he never did work in coal, but my grandfather was an old coal miner.
Well, not really a coal miner, he was from Mexico in them gold mines and silver mines.
But that still was in the ground.
And he came here, he went to work this coal mine, lignite.
So he kind of
I dragged my daddy back this way.
I see.
And that's how we came here.
Do you remember what year you came to Rockdale?
No, I was seven years old.
You're 90 today?
No, not today.
I will be 98 if I live.
Oh, you will.
28th of August, you'll be 98.
That's right.
I was born 1887.
Okay.
The 28th day of August.
All right.
And you came to Rockdale when you were seven years old?
Yes, about seven.
I don't know exactly, but I remember when we came here.
Do you remember how old you were before you started mining yourself?
Yes, my father died when I was 15 years old, and I became the head of the family then.
I had to go to work and see two sisters and two brothers, and I was the oldest one.
So you had to go to work in the mines with your dad?
I had to go to work to make a living for my mother.
In those days, the ladies didn't work like they do today.
I see.
All the work was in the kitchen, in the house.
And so I had to get up and ball the jacks to make a living for five, six hours.
My goodness.
My mother had to sign up some kind of a paper so they would let me go to work.
They didn't want me.
I wasn't allowed to go 15 years of age.
You were too young to work without.
But my mother signed some kind of papers and then they let me go to work.
That's why I lost my leg.
You lost your leg?
Yeah, I got artificial leg.
I see.
I lost it when I was 18 years old.
And you lost it while you were down in one of the mines?
Yes, sir.
Right across back over there.
Vogel's mine.
Vogel's mine?
Vogel's.
I see.
I used to be Vogel's over there.
The side of my house is up here, this side of the railroad, them days.
I see.
Well, how, if you can remember, how did the accident occur?
My late?
Yes, sir.
Well, I was digging coal at that time, and I walked to the, what they call entrance, you know, they had a main entrance.
Right.
And they had rooms turned off from this entrance where the man was digging.
And I got out of my room and I got on.
The driver wasn't going to take my car.
I had a little coal mine car, you know.
We loaded it and then if we loaded it, they had a man to drive a mule.
He'd come and he'd pull the car from it.
And they'd bring you an empty one.
Well, I filled out my car and I dug a big pile of coal and
The driver didn't come, so I started to go out to the main entrance, see what happened.
And when I did, a big rock fell on me.
A big rock fell on you?
Yes, a sand rock.
A big sand rock fell on my back and knocked me down.
And I remember that I had an awful heavy load on me.
I was trying to raise myself, but I couldn't.
Then I passed out.
Now they know nothing.
They dug me out.
They said when they come and see the pile of dirt and the rock and there was a pile of dirt on top of it and they see my shoes, my heels or something.
Said somebody's under here.
They start digging and find my legs and find it.
They do it.
Said it's Augustine.
And they drove me out.
I didn't do it.
Because you were still passed out.
Yeah, I was still passed out.
And they drove me out to a place that had more air, I guess.
And then I come into myself, and man, they couldn't touch me nowhere.
I was hurt all over.
But I come to myself, and then they put me in a sheet and brought me home.
Took you to your home?
Yes, they brought me out, put me on a cage that's sort of like an elevator, you know?
Right.
And they hushed me out, and then they took me to my house.
We was living, all the captain was,
I bet it was a hundred houses just outside of Red Road.
That was Morgan County.
Uh-huh.
It's Morgan.
And they brought me home, and the doctor didn't have the hospital then.
Right.
But we had a company doctor.
Company doctor.
Company doctor, Dr.
Rob Wallace.
Rob Wallace?
Yeah, Dr.
Rob Wallace.
Okay.
Used to be three brothers, Rob, Daddy Wallace.
Dr. Bob Wallace, a little bit of fella.
And then Dr. Doug Wallace, and then Dr.
Rob Wallace.
Three Wallace's.
And... Did they lay you on a cot in your room?
After I got home?
Right.
Yes, they laid me on the bed, I guess.
Layed on my bed, on my cot, I guess.
And then the doctors came and they...
They put, they didn't have this stuff that they use now.
They had this little bowl, this plate as they call it.
And then they put those plates on there and held it there for so many days.
And it didn't grow together.
So the doctor said, I was going to lose my leg if it didn't take it off there.
It was turning black or something.
And my mother got scared, you know, and my older sister.
Says, no, well, take your leg off.
I said, no, I'm going to die or let me die.
No, they won't.
They wouldn't let me.
So they took my leg off, four and a half inches below my kneecap, right along here.
They took my...
The company doctor did that?
Yeah.
Even Dr. Bob, I mean, Dr. Dunkwallis, you see?
Four and a half inches from here, my leg is off right along there.
So you, did you have to pay for the medical attention or did vocal mining have to pay for it?
I had to sue him.
Oh, you sued him?
I had to sue him, yeah.
They wouldn't come across.
They wanted me to vacate the house.
Wanted me and my mother to get out the house because I wasn't able to pay the rent.
So you took him to court then?
So I went and got me a lawyer.
But I did.
Well, I got no sense now, but then as a kid, you know how it is.
No experience or nothing.
So that lawyer got me.
He got more than I got.
But...
The lawyer got more money than you.
Oh, yeah.
You know, he sold out himself.
I see now what happened.
But I couldn't see it then.
But you did get some money from the mining company?
We got $1,000.
$1,000 for my lake.
When I owe the commissary the store, I owe him $700.
Man, that was good enough.
Let my mother buy food on credit.
Right.
And when I got through with him, I paid him $700.
So I had about $300 left.
And I bought my first artificial lake.
Them days didn't cost but $100.
Now they cost $400.
Yeah.
Well, then, so what did you do after you got the money, paid him off, got your artificial lady?
You didn't mine again, did you?
Well, I went to work to mine again, but I didn't go down into mine.
Oh, I see.
I got the job.
I got to learn how to fire, you know, as a fireman, fire boilers.
Fire the boilers.
Yes.
Right.
And they're pumping water out of the mine, so they had to have a man all night long to keep steam up.
for the pumps to run.
And I got a job firing boilers.
I see.
What kind of fuel did you use?
Lignite.
You used the lignite.
Lignite, yeah.
And how long did you have that job?
Oh, I guess, I don't know, for nearly a year, I guess, a month.
Then I began to learn how to run engine.
Then from there, from Wichita, we had to leave Mobile because they made us get out the house.
So we went to Wichita.
And my mother-in-law, the only thing she could make out is run a boarded house.
She kept boarding people, you know, single men.
Oh, she boarded people?
Yeah, she boarded people.
I see.
And that's how I got straight up.
Then we moved to Texas.
Texas Coal Company mine over here.
Oh, you did?
Uh-huh.
And then I went to run the engine, Houston engine.
I was big shot then.
Oh.
Yeah, I could run a Houston engine.
So you didn't go down beneath the ground anymore?
Yes, I went, but not deep coal no more.
I went as a pump man, they called it, you know.
Oh, I see.
As a pump man.
And then for a while, I was a foreman.
A foreman?
Foreman, yeah, I was a boss.
pit boss, they call it.
For a while, not a long time, but for a while.
When you were running the hoist, let's start back when you were stoking the boiler, how were you paid?
I was paid by the month.
By the month, okay.
And then when you became an engineer, by the month.
And then when you were a foreman, by the month.
Do you remember how much you were paid per month?
Let's see, I was getting, I don't remember what, we worked 12 hours.
I went to work six in the morning to six at night, at evening.
And, uh,
I don't remember how much I got when I was fine, but when I rode the engine, I got $90 a month.
$90 a month for being an engineer.
For engineer, yeah.
That was 12 hours a day.
Five days a week?
Six days a week.
Six days a week.
What about when you were a foreman?
Same thing.
$90 a month?
$90, yeah, the same.
I didn't stay long as a foreman.
Mr. Taylor, Sam Taylor was a foreman.
And he had to go to Houston, bought something, and he left it in his place for about a month or so.
I didn't stay long.
Then he quit, and they put this woman there, the Texas Gold Company, that was Mr. E.B.
Phillips.
E.B.
Phillips, right.
And Mr. St. Kitts, Shrivlin, Mr. Shrivlin.
Shrivlin?
Shrivlin was the superintendent.
And the storekeeper.
And E.B.
Phillips and H.C. Meyer was there.
The big, there was a big shot.
There was only place there or something.
Do you remember what kind of a man E.B.
Phillips was?
He was a big-style fellow, and he talked and cussed like dickens.
Every time he moved his mouth, he'd cuss.
He'd cuss over the phone and everywhere, every time.
I remember one time when I was buying the boilers, it was the wintertime, and they had a haul of water, and they had a digger on a wagon with some burners, you know.
And he got, it was so cold, he didn't want to go after more water.
So I was getting out of water, and I called Mr. Phillips, I said,
Mr. Phillip, I said, with my guy, why did the ass run over that goddamn nigga?
I said, well, it's too cold.
He don't want to get out.
I'll be there in a minute.
I'll make the setup.
He's going to wake up.
His mouth will move.
Over the phone, he cussed.
He didn't care.
He was that kind of man.
He was a good-hearted man, all right.
Good-hearted?
Yeah, Mr. Phillip was a good man.
Yes, sir.
How long did you work for the Texas Colt Company?
Oh, I don't know.
I worked out many years.
I would look at the letter that I got from them, you know.
They give me when I quit.
They give me a big letter, recommendation, you know.
I don't want to work on them.
For them, that I was a dependable man and all this and that.
I got a letter that's somewhere.
Yeah, I'd like to see that later on, maybe, if we could.
Well, my wife, she can't hardly get up now.
She's in bed.
Well, if we can't find it, that's all right.
But from what I know, the Texas Coal Company mine started to really phase out about the mid-20s, mid-late 20s.
Yes.
Is that right?
During the war.
Or after the war?
And after the war, yeah.
They closed up.
Why did they close up?
I don't know.
Oh, I think Alcoa put them out of business.
Well, Alcoa didn't come in until...
So I was just wondering if maybe the Depression didn't hurt coal companies.
Do you remember what you did during the Depression?
Sure.
I was already moved here.
I was already had quit.
You know, after I quit Texas Coal Company, I bought me an automobile that went to run ginning.
I run ginning for about a year and a half, for two years.
You ran a gin?
A ginning?
a service car for about a year and a half.
I see.
Were you able to save money working at the Texas Gold Company?
Not too much, but I saved something.
Yes, I saved something.
I married in 1919.
And I had a little money when I married.
Had been saving, you know, holding back.
Then after I married, I bought me a car.
In 1919, I married in 1920, I think.
This girl was married to my oldest daughter.
She was born in 1920.
And that was a brand new Ford.
Model T or Model A?
Model T. Model T. Model T. They had no Model As yet.
They came in a little late afterwards.
It was Model T. It had courage on its side.
No, no, no glasses, nothing like that.
I see.
No, I had curtains.
Curtains?
Yeah, and a cloth top.
You know, you could put it back or raise it up any way you wanted.
So you didn't go back to the mines after you quit?
No, after I quit, I didn't go back.
I moved here.
Then I bought this little place of land here, an old house that used to be out there, right there close to where the fence is now.
And then I went to work for the city.
City Water Works.
At Rockdale.
At Rockdale, yeah.
That work that I doing, worked for the city about two, three years.
Then I quit the city and I went to plumbing by myself, you know, my own job.
I was a plumber.
A plumber.
Plumber until I retired.
Well, that sounds great.
If we could go back, you know, to your days at the Texas Coal Company, okay, could you describe a typical day

at the mine you know what time did you get up in the morning what did you do well my job was i had to get up i i didn't get up in the morning i went to work and i was working at night you see okay 12 hours i went to work at six in the in the evening and and quit six in the morning i see then mr mr uh summers the old man he come in and take the day
They called it shifts.
I was working that shift and he was working this shift.
They said I was young and he was old, man.
They let him work.
I told him, that's all right.
I could stand the 12 hours of work.
And I did for years and I don't know how long.
What did you do during your 12-hour shift?
Fired boilers, keeping the steam up and watching my pumps.
They were on 12 hours all night, keep that water on.
He pumped the water out of the mine.
See, they had a flood here one time.
The water broke in the mine and yellow fell up to the top.
And they had to pump water day and night there for a long time.
Several weeks or?
Months.
Months?
Yes, yes.
Months.
And you lived right next to the mines, right?
Oh, we lived at the camps, you see.
The camp had houses.
Oh, I had rows of houses, one here, one there, and just, you know, about every 40 feet, one from the other.
Two-room house.
Two-room house.
Yes, one room and a kitchen, little old kitchen, yes.
About as big as my garage size.
How many people would live in these?
Well, some of them had just a man and a wife, and some of them had two or three children, or some of them had four or five kids, and they all lived in that one room.
Yeah.
See, when I first married, my mother was running a boarding house.
She had a big four-room house.
That's a boarded house.
A boarding house.
Yeah, and four rooms.
One room, she kept that for the dining room for there.
When the men come to eat, that big room, and three rooms for my sister, she stayed.
And after I was married, when I move out, then I went and rent one of those small houses just
Me and my wife, you know.
Right.
Do you know, do you remember how much the company charged you to live in those houses?
Yes, the small house was $3 a month.
$3 a month.
And that big house where my mother lived was $6 a month.
I see.
Yeah.
Well, did your mother's boarding house belong to the mine?
Yeah, to the company.
I see.
To the company, yes.
What kind of men would come and board there?
Well, working men, working, working in the mine, coal diggers.
Oh.
Would it be bachelors most of them?
Yeah, bachelors, sure.
Bachelors.
They had no wives.
They're bachelors.
They're single men, they call it.
Single men.
Single men.
Yeah, mother had this room, this six, I mean, this whole room of house.
It's a boarded house.
Then they covered it with rent.
It's a mortar house.
They had carts for them.
Single men sleep, you know.
That's $3 a month.
But mother didn't have to pay for that.
Each one of them.
Mrs. Trevlin, he took charge of that.
He charged everyone, I don't know how much, but mother didn't have to do with that.
All she had to do was to make a four-room house.
She had to pay rent for that.
And then, did the men pay her for cooking?
Oh, yes.
She charged them for that.
I believe it was $3 a week.
Three hours a week?
Yeah, for cooking.
And the grub, not only cooking, but the groceries and everything.
Yes, served the table.
All that dude sat on the table and ate.
She served them three meals a day?
Three meals a day.
Yes, sir.
Did they come up out of the mines for lunch?
They usually take lunch at dinner time.
Very seldom.
Very few of them come out at noon.
They go down in the morning.

didn't come out about started coming out from three to four o'clock well did your mother fix them a supper to take down into the mind at dinner yes that's bigger lunch she fixed the lunch for them so for instance if i say well i'm not coming to dinner today fix me a lunch please all right mother fixing my life and i take my lunch with me so i wouldn't be she wouldn't expect me to be there at noon
Because I already took my lunch, you see.
Well, if the miners came out between 3 and 4, what did they do after they finished the day of mining?
They just sat around and talked.
Sit around and talked.
Yeah.
What did they do on the weekends?
Same thing.
Same thing?
Same thing.
They had a big wash, a bathroom place there.
right close to the agent house, concrete floor.
They were there going to shoot dice, most of them.
They spent time shooting dice, playing poker or some kind of game.
But they spent Sundays and Saturday nights over there.
I see.
In the camp.
Would they ever go into Rockville?
Oh, yes, they'd go on Saturday evenings and buy their beer and bring it back, or maybe they'd get drunk and down.
Some of them would drink one in the morning.
Mr. Stribble had to go and pay the fines to get them out.
They had to come and work it, pay the fine.
Was that fine taken out of their paycheck?
Oh, sure.
Yeah, sure.
They had to pay it all.
Of course, Mr. Stribble would give them time to say,
For instance, if a man had just $15 coming through the week, and the flight was $20 or $50, he'd take out, say, maybe $5 this payday.
Next payday, he'd take another $5.
Then he'd pay his pay.
Yeah, he'd give him a chance.
He'd give him a break.
Yeah, the other street was pretty nice.
Was there any type of musical instruments around the camps at all?
No.
No, every now and then, maybe once, maybe some, maybe one or two of us used to play horns or violin or something.
They had dances all right.
They did?
Yeah, they had dances about every two, three Saturday nights.
Was that in the camp?
In the camp.
They had a big hall over there.
Company made up a big hall.
I see.
Was that over at the Vogel Mine?
That was at Texas Mine.
They had a dance hall?
They had a dance hall at Texas Mine.
Do you remember where most of the miners came from?
Oh, they came from all over the country, I think.
They used to send a man to Laredo to get some hands, to get some coal diggers.
They'd bring a bunch of people over there.
Sometimes eight or 10, sometimes three or four, just that way.
Some of them were families, lots of them were single, but they'd bring them in.
They'd send the men, they were down there, to Laredo, or Salentown, or somewhere, to get some men.
Were they, had they already been miners in Mexico, or were they new to New Mexico?
No, some of them maybe, there was some of them.
They'd never seen a mine before, I don't reckon.
But they claimed they was a miner.
Did they think that the conditions here were better than in New Mexico?
I guess so, they liked it.
They liked it here?
They liked it here in the United States, yeah.
They still like it because I see lots of them white bikes coming this way.
They still like it.
You're a natural citizen because you were born here.
Oh, I was born here, raised here, this side of Austin.
Yeah, all my life.
Yeah, I was born in Austin, Texas, Travis County.
First of my life, the week before last.
I look at the captain and I says, I wonder what was that boy, somebody lose check again?
So far.
That's a long time ago.
Long time ago.
Did, Augustine, do you remember any labor problems at the Texas Coal Company mine?
Were there any strikes or any union movements or anything?
No, there ain't no union.
No, they had no strikes.
Well, what if one of the workers got mad at Mr. Phillips or something?
Did he just quit and leave, or what did he do?
Well, if they get mad, they just quit that mine and go find a job at the other one.
You see, there was a world of mine, and here was a Vogel's right across there, and that was a Texas, and that was a big lump far on yonder.
There was four, five shafts.
There was hundreds and hundreds of coal diggers.
So if I did mess with my boss here or something, I just quit, go with the other place, get me a job, and go to work.
And maybe one for over there, come over here, just that way.
I see.
Well, did you work all year long?
Huh?
Did you work all the year?
Yes, sure, all year long.
Yeah, we had no vacation then.
No vacation.
No, sir.
You know what vacation was?
No retirement plan, no.
When you got too old and you couldn't do the job, it's just like an old mule that turns you loose in the pasture.
Gone.
You can't do no more good while it's gone.
It ain't like now.
No, I lost the best part of my life.
I wish I had the more, but
40 years later than I was born.
Why is that?
Because it's different now.
Whole lot of different than it was when I was a young man.
See, when I was a young man, I go to work at 6 in the morning.
If I'm one hour late, they send me home and they wouldn't let me work.
And if I quit one hour earlier, they took it off my check.
If you wait three hours, you get paid for three hours, rain or shine, whether you had the reason or not.
You wait three hours, six days, that's all you get paid for.
But nowadays, you start to work, you get full time.
And after you get so old, that you're 65 years old, you get Social Security, you get retirement from the railroad, all that protection.
Well, back yonder when I was a young man, was nothing like that.
When I got a lot of good work, they just kicked my butt and gone.
Kicked me out.
Said, you're putting out a young man in this place.
That's the way the combine used to be.
Well, did anybody take care of you then?
Families or friends?
Nobody, nobody.
You just kicked it out on your own?
If you had it, you eat it.
If you didn't have it, you wouldn't eat it.
You'd starve.
No, it ain't like it is now, not there.
No, no.
No, back in them days, if you had a piece of bread, you'd eat it.
If you didn't have it, what?
You just didn't have it?
No, it was over.
What happened when somebody got sick?
Did the other families help out?
Yes, we got to take up collections.
We'd go around and say, so-and-so's at a badge.
How much can you have?
Well, a quarter maybe, half a dollar, or whatever you could.
And we take a list to the store, to Mr. Stribling, and give it to him.
He says, for instance, I'll go half a dollar, all right, Augustine?
He says, you go half a dollar, so-and-so half a dollar, and on and on.
We give Mr. Stribling the list, and he take it all right.
So that made his wife, or his daughter, to come to the store and buy it.
If you had $4 worth, well, you'd get $4 worth of grub.
That's why we take up collections, you know, to help them.
Somebody die, we take up a collection to pay for the coffin.
Yeah, you see, while we was in the mine, someone with a book, piece of paper, the person, oh, somebody passed away.
So and so died last night.
How much can you put on here to help?
Oh, maybe a dollar or a dollar and a half, something like that.
Whatever you could, $2.
Well, okay.
They bring the list to Mr. Smith's store.
Okay.
He said, sit down, says, let's have a coffee for so much.
They got $20 collected here or $30, $40 or $50, whatever you want.
Let them have it.
We got nothing to worry about.
That's the way it is.
But some men got killed at the mine.
They wouldn't give them a penny, not even a coffin.
